    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nHi, I would really like a way to both indent text and jump to the end of it.\nSuch an addition would behave similarly to what `gp` does compared to `p`.\n\nThis could be particularly useful when manually indenting multiple regions in a file, as reading and fixing them sequentially from top to bottom is currently less doable than bottom to top.\n\nTo avoid conflicts with existing commands, maybe this could only be enabled in visual modes as `g<` / `g>`, and in normal mode as `<g` / `>g`.\n\nI understand that this normal mode addition is not satisfactory, since the operator/motion order is not respected.\nMaybe this second part of my feature request could be skipped.\n\n**Current behavior**: consider the following text:\n\n```\nfo bar baz\nfo bar baz\nfo bar baz\n```\n\nSelecting the entire paragraph then inputting `>`, or using something like `>ip`, both reset the cursor to the start of the paragraph once the indentation changes.\n\nI know a 10-line function can be written in a config file to save the cursor position, execute the action, then set the cursor position back, but this feels like something that should not be necessary.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nInside a file, one could select some lines, then input something like `g>` to indent these lines and place the cursor on the last one instead of the first.",
