            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> 1. To preserve dot repeat, we need to reimplement shifting in lua, which causes some slight flashing with inlay hints where the text disappears and reappears. This would be fixed if we had [Most recently used text-object, `v:motion` #19426](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/19426). I think virtual text could also be more intelligent here, as it temporarily puts the text onto the next line for some reason.\n> 2. We need to remap `.` to store the position of the cursor before dot repeating. This is a bit hacky, but without it, dot repeating after moving the cursor will \"rubberband\" the cursor back to where it originally was.\n> 3. On undo, the cursor will go to the top of the textobject range, rather than the location you expected it to.\n\n1. Instead of setting lines, couldn't you set or remove indentation at the front of the line using nvim_buf_set_text? I think that would just move the inlay hint extmarks. Or do you still get the flashing because the LSP re-generates them?\n2. If you're on a LuaJIT build, the keyStuffed C global is true if you're in the middle of a dot repeat (f/t checks if this is true to see if it should re-use the previous input). If not FFI, you can use an on_key callback to set a dot-repeating flag, then vim.schedule to unset it (Flash does this). You can use that to conditionally access caches.\n3. Would be another on_key callback, but maybe you could listen on undo and check operatorfunc == your_function and v:operator == \"g@\". But then what if the user re-maps undo.",
