            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Indeed, `nvim_buf_set_text` fixes the virtual text issues. Edited the code snippet to use it. \n\nFor fun, I tried to only call `vim.text.indent` once on the entire line range, then just take substrings of it in the loop:\n```lua\n  local unindented_lines = vim.api.nvim_buf_get_lines(0, first_lnum, last_lnum, true)\n  local joined_lines = table.concat(unindented_lines, \"\\n\")\n  local _, shared_indent = vim.text.indent(0, joined_lines)\n  joined_lines = vim.text.indent(shared_indent + shiftwidth * sign, joined_lines, { expandtab = 1 })\n  local indented_lines = vim.split(joined_lines, \"\\n\")\n```\nBut the way `shared_indent` behaves means that if you try to dedent these two lines:\n```\nfirst line unindented\n  second line indented\n```\nIt won't dedent them at all. This differs from `<`, which indents every line that it's able to. I'm not sure if there's a good way to do this, so I stuck with the current version.",
